1. The reform on electricity supply issues and land plot allocation has been developed with support from the project. During the pilot testing of newly introduced reforms several issues revealed such as high cost of service on connecting to electricity and absence of clear and transparent criteria of assessment of application submitted for land plots.
In this regard, project assisted in further improvement of mechanism to connect to electric networks by setting: 
- Strict time and cost limitations for development of the Architectural and technical objectives; 
- order, time and cost of development of topographic maps; 
- procedure for determining the cost of the “turn-key” services;
- guidance on developing a contract and its estimated value to connect business entities to electric networks on a "turn-key" principle:
by setting a minimum list of costs associated with contractual and construction documents;
by setting a model regular number of employees for each territorial unit to increase efficiency;
- establishing a procedure to monitor electricity supply (based on SAIDI and SAIFI indices), including unplanned shutdowns, keeping the total duration and frequency of unplanned outages within established limits, and disclosure of the monitoring results on the official website of energy company.
As for the land plot allocation, with the support of the Project, national counterparts, developed guidelines for commissions on conducting tenders for land plots allocation for entrepreneurs. As a result, announcements on tenders in all regions of Uzbekistan placed at https://my.gov.uz/ru/page/realEstate websites. Criteria for selection of successful bidders approved, which clarifies and improves transparency of land plot allocation process.
The Action Plan («Roadmap») on improving regulatory framework and streamlining procedures, in the areas evaluated by World Bank under the Doing Business methodology, elaborated by the project and approved by the Cabinet on August 3, 2016.

1. With the assistance of the Project a package of recommendations for further improvement of business climate is prepared and submitted to the Government on June 19, 2017 by #3/ASh-13-3284, which includes:
- draft Government Resolution “On further measures to improve business environment in Uzbekistan” that establishes an effective framework for conducting feasibility study, developing amendments to laws and regulations in consultation with private sector, improving law enforcement practice on annual basis;
- approval of the Road map on further improving regulatory framework and streamlining procedures. The Road map includes specific recommendations on improving legislation and its practical implementation in the areas, covered by the Doing business report;
- establishes an interagency working group to coordinate implementation of the Road map. 
Discussions of the Road map with wide range of stakeholders and public through online public review mechanisms (regulation.gov.uz) was completed on August 15, 2017.
In order to improve factors influencing county's ranking assessed in various international rankings, project developed and offered to national partners the following recommendations: 
- to improve factors influencing “Global Indicators of Regulatory Governance" the recommendations developed and submitted to the national partners on January 30, 2017 by #7/ASh-13-480, which includes: 1) analysis of shortfalls identified in the national law and regulations drafting procedures, 2) measures to overcome those shortfalls;
- to improve factors influencing “Global Competitiveness Report” the recommendations developed and submitted to national partner on April 18, 2017 by #551D, which include: a) revision of basis of interaction of government agencies with private sector, b) accelerate development of infrastructure (transport, auto- and rail roads, sustainable water and electric supply, telecommunication network) for industrial companies to operate, c) ensure stable macr
